Japanese Stocks in U.S., Australian Futures Rise on Commodities

-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 
2011-05-24T23:14:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-24/japanese-stocks-in-u-s-australia-futures-rise-on-higher-commodity-prices.html
Japanese stocks traded in the U.S.
rose after commodities prices increased and as the yen weakened
against the euro, boosting the outlook for overseas earnings.
Australian stock futures advanced.  The Bank of New York Mellon  Japan  ADR Index gained 0.6
percent yesterday. American depositary receipts of  Canon Inc. (7751) , a
camera maker that gets more than 80 percent of its sales abroad,
gained 0.3 percent from the closing share price in Tokyo. Those
of Honda Motor Co., Japan’s second-largest automaker, advanced
0.5 percent after Deutsche Bank AG increased its profit estimate
for the company. ADRs of  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , the world’s largest
mining company, increased 0.8 percent.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,475 in  Chicago  yesterday, compared with 9,480
in Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,480 in
Osaka, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on  Australia ’s S&P/ASX
200 Index gained 0.1 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index
advanced 0.6 percent in Wellington.  “Commodity prices still remain on an upward trend, even
though the pace is slowing, as the global economy is not
deteriorating,” said  Hiroichi Nishi , an equities manager in
 Tokyo  at SMBC Nikko Securities Inc. “The weakening yen is
positive for Japanese stocks.”  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. In New York, the index fell 0.1 percent to
1,316.28 yesterday as a drop in stocks most-tied to economic
growth offset a government report showing that sales of new
homes rose to the highest level this year.  Manufacturing Shrinks  A report from the Commerce Department showed yesterday U.S.
purchases of new houses climbed 7.3 percent to a 323,000 annual
pace in April after plunging to a record low two months earlier.
The median estimate in a Bloomberg News survey of economists was
for 300,000 sales.  The Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond’s manufacturing index
slid to negative six in May, compared with a reading of 10 in
April and a forecast of nine in a Bloomberg News survey of
economists.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 4.3 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with a gain of 4.7 percent by the
 S&P 500  and a drop of 0.2 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.
Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at 13.3 times estimated
earnings on average, compared with 13.3 times for the S&P 500
and 11 times for the Stoxx 600.  Crude Oil Jumps  Crude oil for July delivery jumped 1.9 percent to $99.59 a
barrel in  New York  yesterday, the highest settlement since May
18. The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six industrial
metals including copper and aluminum increased 1.2 percent
yesterday.  The yen depreciated to 116.18 against the euro, compared
with 115.14 at the close of  stock trading  in Tokyo yesterday. A
weaker yen boosts the value of overseas income at Japanese
companies when converted into their home currency.  Deutsche Bank raised its profit estimate for Honda and
Nissan Motor Co., citing higher car sales. The brokerage
projected Honda will have an operating profit of 500.3 billion
yen ($6.1 billion) in the year ending in March 2012, compared
with its earlier estimate of 250.4 billion yen. It increased its
profit estimate for Nissan to 480 billion yen from 149.5 billion
yen.  To contact the reporters on this story:
